The only line likely to cause `strtol()` to be invoked is the call to `atoi()` - the call stack in the debugger will confirm that.

Both here:

    p = strtok(line, &quot; &quot;);
    v[i] = atoi(p);

and here:

        p = strtok(NULL,&quot; &quot;);
        v[i] = atoi(p);

you fail to check `p != NULL` before passing it to `atoi()`.  From [Microsoft&#39;s documentation][1]:

&gt; If the parameter passed in is NULL, the invalid parameter handler is
&gt; invoked, as described in [Parameter Validation][2]. If execution is allowed
&gt; to continue, these functions set errno to EINVAL and return 0.

A simple reorganisation of your code will both reduce complexity _and_ fix the failure to check for NULL:

    p = strtok(line, &quot; &quot;);
    while (p != NULL)
    {
        v[i] = atoi(p);
        i++;
        p = strtok(NULL,&quot; &quot;);
    }

The code was always wrong, but undefined behaviour is exactly that.  Both tools include a debugger, Visual Studio being the superior debugger, even if its C support is stuck in 1989.  The Call stack window will have allowed you to observe the local variables of the calling function (`main()` in this case), and you will have seen `p == NULL`.  Really; learn to use the debugger effectively - much faster than posting questions!

  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/cpp/c-runtime-library/reference/atoi-atoi-l-wtoi-wtoi-l?view=vs-2019
  [2]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/cpp/c-runtime-library/parameter-validation?view=vs-2019

